szy: Midayhiw to Syifo ci Cayinwen Congtong mioyamali to Incomin a codad
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

szy: ayaw no tosa bataan izao ko tosa a mihcaan ayza a demiad, i tini i holic to "sanpaw" hananay balican to"Incomin"hanto. nipangangan toyni, o mibakahay to misawacoay a piawaw, katinengan o Incomin i Taywan"i tinitiniay aca a tademaw" sananay. o angangan no kamo koyni, ayza, taayawen ko awas no mita. midayhiw kako to Syifo, misoayaw to polong no Incomin a tademaw, patahkal to naybaloco'ay a pioyamali. namakayza ayaw no sepat lasobo a mihcaan, o pisamsam pisepen pisawaco sakalabades namo, midayhiw kako to Syifo, mioyamali i tamowan.
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

szy: patatenga' kako, katokoh ayza, i labo no mita, izao henay ko sapihica mioyamali sananay a tademaw. wini sa, izayhan o saka pidayhiw no mako to Syifo mioyamali.mahica o mamahinihini ko itawyaay sananay, saca ato, o labades no zoma a binacadan, mahinihini aca ko nikaozip no tademaw sananay, wini ko sapotizeng no mako ayza i tini, maydih a pasasiyol mibalic to mahiniay a nizateng.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

szy: pakayzaen ako i alodayay a kamo, kiya patahkal to nabaloco'an ako mioyamali. Ina lala' i Taywan, ayaw no sepat a lasobo no mihcaan izao to ko tademaw. tademaw itini nakapah ko nikaozip, izao ko no teked a kamo, bonka, aloday, sakaozip.kilol sa, caay patobeli koheni sa, ina aenengan debongan no zoma a tademaw.
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

szy: polekal no likisi sa, debongan no tao, alawan kiya itiniay a tademaw. sakainaynayi' no sakaozip ato aenengan malopisak to koheni, mahiza to o palabangay, nayi' to ko hahohahol a maozip. Sakasilahci no cacay a binacadan, hakay namakayzaay i pisawaco to zoma a binacadan. caay pikamo to kao motelekay a kanatal kami asa, tabakien ko piazih tina likisi itawya, patahkalen misakamo ko tatenga'ay a likisi. Zikoz sa, o matatongosay, o Syifo kanca pisazatezateng to itawyaay a kawaw, wini ko sapotizeng ako itini ayza a demiad.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

szy: izao ko cacay a codad "Taywan tongse" sananay. saayaway a kamo hinisa; "inayi' ko likisi no Taywan. Amohwan ko palekalay, Cencenkong ko misanga'ay, kokong ko milekoay."mahini ko no layak a piazih to nakawawan a likisi. Incomin a binacadan, ayaw no pinapina malebot a mihcaan, itini to a maozip, kadobah ko bonka ato taneng, masalaylay katokoh wawa no wawa wawa. nika, paicelang sa kami o niyam a piazih ko picodad i likisi, wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo mioyamali to Incomin.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

szy: Amohwan ato ci Cencenkong kawaw no heni to Pinpoco a binacadan mipacok to tademaw ato mialaw to kalisiw, no Kokong pikowan o satabakiay a kawaw mipatay ato misawaco, kaLiponan mitesek ko pikowan to Incomin, katokoh nazikozan malalais i kaHolaman mikawaw to boyo'ay saenalen ko pikawan. sepat lasobo a mihcaan, kahacacay no tayniay i Taywan a mikowanay, pakayzaen i kowang mibolibol, mialaw to lala', tadamalawlaw ko kawaw no Incomin. wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo mioyamali to Incomin.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

szy: aloday no laylay i niyazo' malalid ko kawaw no Incomin, ato malalid kapah ko taneng mikowan to kalotood. nika, imahini teban no pipatizeng no kanatal to likec, malawpes ko nizateng no Incomin to kawaw, ato teked no Incomin a pikowan. lalay no niyazo' sakalawpes, tongos akawaw no binacadan caay ka pisolol. wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo mioyamali to Incomin.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

szy: na izao ko kamo no Incomin, milakec to pikowan no hongti no kaLiponan, ato 1945 a mihcaan sa, la'cos mosakamo to kamo namo han no Syifo, masa pihaceng ko nika lawpes no kamo. yadah to ko malawpesay a kamo no Pinpoco. hatiniay to a Syifo, makayza i no bonka a laylay no Incomin caay kataneng ko pidipot, wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo mioyamali to Incomin.
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

szy: somamad, maliyoh ko Botod a tademaw to kawaw no Syifo, to pipazeng i Botod to kinabakah no misadingkiay a hefyiliaw. i Botoday a tademaw mihadidi to misawaco no kinabakah no misadingkiay a hefyiliaw. wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo mioyamali to Botoday a tademaw.
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government.

szy: yo debongan no tao ko Taywan sa, maloayaayaw ko sa'tipay a Pinpoco abinacadan masamsam. palawpesan no tayniay mikowan ko Pinpoco a tademaw, wini sa, a midayhiw kako to Syifo, mioyamali to Pinpoco.
english: Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

szy: yo mabalic to ko sakibinacadan a kawaw, napatobeli ko kanatal to pilongoc no Incomin. paloayaw to ko Syifo patobeli, namisaicelang to to kawaw. imahini, izao to ko kapahay "angangan no holic no Incomin," nika, inaholic, caay kaimata no Syifo. caay kakalamkam ko kawaw niyam, caay kahamin, caay kataneng. wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo, mioyamali to Incomin.
english: After the democratic transition, the country began to respond to the appeals of indigenous movements. The government made certain promises and efforts. Today, we have an Indigenous Peoples Basic Law that is quite advanced. However, government agencies have not given sufficient weight to this law. Our actions have not been fast enough, comprehensive enough or sound enough. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

szy: sikamo ko Taywan "yadahay kasasizoma no bonka" a binacadan. nika, katokoh ayza, payni i sakatanektek no ozip no Incomin, pasobana', sakaozip a kalisiw, ato pilihiza to cence a kawaw, caay kahiza o no layak. ato wiza henay tawyaay ko nipiazih to Incomin, ozoma misawaco henay, caay henay kalawpes. caay kataneng ko kawaw no Syifo to saki Incomin, caay henay pilakec ko zomaay a binacadan to malitemohay no Incomin a kawaw, ato malitemohay a labades ato ngelo'. wini sa, midayhiw kako to Syifo, mioyamali to Incomin.
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

szy: caay kataneng ko pisaicelang niyam, nano somamad katokoh ayza, caay kakalamkam a katinengan caay kataneng ko pisaicelang niyam, sisa o ngelo' namo, katokoh imahini. tatenga' hicaen naca haw. ayzaay a pioyamali, ano matenetenes ko nikaotang, nika o piteka koyni. caay pizateng kako sepat lasoboay to a mihcaan ko labades no Incomin, wini a nicodadan to sasakamoen ako, pioyamali hakay caay pakalopay to baloco namo. nika mihalhal kako, ayzaay pioyamali, lalabo no kanatal a tademaw ita mitekaay pasayza i kasasosolol.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

szy: pasakamoen ako to sitanengay a kamo no Incomin, ayzaay a saopo. kamo no Tayalo,"tatenga'ay," Balay han noheni. o"masasolol"Sbalay han, conosen i noayawan no Balay ko S a ngiha'. tatenga'ay ato masasonga'ay o malecaday i nizateng. zoma sato sa, tatenga'ay a masasolol, payni i tatenga'ay nabaloco'an misoayaw a dada', itawya taneng malaheci ko kawaw.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

szy: i lalabo no bonka no Incomin, ano misala'cos to niyazo'ay ko cacay a tademaw, maydih masasolol sa, pasaopoen no kalas koheni, masasoayaw caay pikasenon mioyamali, papipatahkalen henay to i baloco'ay. mahamin pasakamo sa, papienipen no kalas to epah, itawyaay ko itawyaay sato. Sbalay han koyni.
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

szy: wini ko nihalhalan no mako a saopo, o no Syifo ato Incomia a Sbalay. o ngangaw i somamad, tatenga'ay a kawaw i somamad, hamin han no mako patahkal mosakamo. ano sawni, Incamin a salikaka, a pasakamo to nabaloco'an. matalaw kako milongoc to pisolol namo ayza, nika, milongoc kako to pihalhal no binawlan, caay to piliyaw ko no samamaday ngangaw, wini a kanatal, hakay ano yaan to a demiad, tanengay a masasolol.
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

szy: mitekaay to ayza a demiad, a masasonga'ay hakiya, caay kai Incomin ato Pinpoco abinacadan, o Syifo ko sikawaway. matineng kako, tanolaway sa mioyamali caay katatongos, mikawawan i Incomin, itini a katinengan ko no kanatal a tatengay taneng masasolol asa.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

szy: itini kako patahkal to kamo, a patizeng ko Congtongfo to"Incomico motelekay likisi ato masasiyol motelekay sakakapah a Wyiyinhoyi."a o kako o kakelidan no kanatal, ko pasaopoay, ato dayhiw no paybinacada mikilim to tatenga'ay likisi, a pasepadacen ko katatengil to kakawawen no kanatal ano ayaw.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

szy: paicelang kako misakamo, Congtongfo a Wiyinhoyi, takalawen ko piazih, o kanatal ato Incomin malecaday masepadacay. sakaizao no paybinacadan a dayhiw, ato Pinpoco, a o binacadan ato niyazo'ay a piazih ko maloangangan no kawaw. wini a kawaw, a o kalacacay no piketon no Incomin to kawaw, kapah a patahkal ko binacadan to tatenga'ay a nabaloco'an.
english: I want to stress that this commission places the greatest importance on equality between the country and the indigenous peoples. The election of tribal representatives, including for the Pingpu ethnic group, will take as basis the consensus of peoples and tribes. This commission will serve as a mechanism for collective decision-making by indigenous peoples, and will ensure that the voices of tribe members find true expression.

szy: ozoma sa to, a milongoc kako to Sincenyin a pasaopo"micozohay to Incomin angangan no holic a saopo."o kalacacay no sasakamoen no Wiyanhoyi, ano ayaw o Syifo, a palacacay mikawaw to kawaw. kawaw namin sa mikilim to mazatengay likisi, micozoh to Incomin cece, malecad ko kasikalisiw, sapasobana' ato palaylay to bonka, ato sakatanektek to ozip, sakakapah no i toseay a binacadan.
english: In addition, I will request that our Executive Yuan convene regularly the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law Promotion Committee, and use the Yuan's authority to coordinate and handle matters related to any consensus reached by the above-mentioned commission. These matters include the following: to retrieve historical memories, to promote indigenous self-government, to seek fair economic development, to ensure continuation of culture and education, to safeguard indigenous health, and to protect the rights of urban indigenous peoples, etc.

szy: ayzaay a holic ato laylay no bonka no Incomin, yadah ko caay kalecad, patizeng kami to izaoay ko bonka a "pipadangan to hilic no Incomin," pakayzaen i holic, milopay to bonka no Incomin ato lalabo no holic no kanatal, yadah ko masasoadaay.
english: Where modern laws and indigenous traditional cultures are at odds, we will set up an Indigenous Legal Service Center with a high degree of cultural sensitivity, to reduce through institutional design the growing clashes between indigenous customs and modern laws.

szy: milongoc kami to sitongosay to kawaw, kalamkamen milosimet, zayhan lalay a kawaw no Incomin, i lalabo no kaozipan a lala', caay kao idih pacakay, miadop caay ko mamalawpesay a aadopen ko niadopan, o mamalobo ato maloboay to. mahiniay kawaw, masasakamo kita a hicaen miholak.
english: I will ask the relevant agencies to immediately pull together cases in which indigenous community members have been indicted or sentenced for hunting, where the hunting was done in accordance with traditional customs, on traditional lands, and for non-transactional needs, and where the animals hunted were not protected by conservation laws. For such cases we will deliberate solutions.

szy: milongoc kako to sitongosay to kawaw, pipazen to kinabakah no misadinkiay to hefyiliaw i Botod mahicaay ko piketon to kawaw, patahkalen cimaay koyza. ayaw no pilimad to kinabakah no misadinkiay to hefyiliaw, pabelien to ko Yamiay a tademaw to kalisiw.
english: I will also direct relevant agencies to present an investigative report on the decision-making process of nuclear waste storage on Orchid Island. Before finding a permanent solution for the nuclear waste, we will provide the Yami tribe appropriate compensation.

szy: ato kasikazen to ko Pinpoco a binacadan to pisakako noheni, Incomin kako sananay, kami i ayaw no siwa a bolad tolo bataan a demiad, a matatengil to mahicaay a holic, saka kapah no Pinpoco a tanengay ko noheni miteked.
english: At the same time, under the principle of respecting the Pingpu ethnic group's self- identity, and recognizing their identity, we will examine relevant laws before September 30 of this year, so that Pingpu ethnic group identity will receive the rights and status it deserves.

szy: ayza a mihca cacay bataan izao ko cacay a bolad cacay a demiad, miteka kami to kawaw, patahkal to no Incomin a sakaozip a lala'.pakaholican to ko saopo no niyazo', malaheci to masaongay niyam, ano ayaw, nabaloco'an no Incomin a misateked, a hacacay asa malaheci. sakalamkamen niyam, kasimataan no Incomin a"pisateked no Incomin a holic,""no lala'ay ato bayoay no Incomi a holic,""sapalekal to kamo no Incomin a holic"a kawaw, patayzaen i Lifayin papiazih.
english: On November 1 of this year, we will begin to delineate and announce indigenous traditional territories and lands. The system of tribal public corporation is already in place. In the future, the ideals of indigenous self-government will be realized step by step. We will step up the pace and submit for legislative deliberation three laws of great importance to indigenous peoples: the Indigenous Peoples Self-Government Law, the Indigenous Peoples Land and Sea Areas Law, and the Indigenous Languages Development Law.

szy: ayza namalahok, a masaopo kami to pakayzaay i no Incomin a kaygi. labo no kaygi, pasakamo to yadahay a kawaw no Syifo. paymihca waloay bolad cacay demiad, pasakamoen no Syifo ko polong no Incomin to nikawawan to binacadan likisi ato misomad to la'cosay palakapah a nakawawan. milahci mikawaw to tatenga'ay a likisi, patizeng to angangan no piteked no Incomin, o Syifo Incomin toloay a sasoayawen a kawaw.
english: Later this afternoon, we will convene a national indigenous peoples administrative meeting. In that meeting, the government will elaborate on the policies. On every August 1 to come, the Executive Yuan will report to the indigenous peoples our progress on restoring historical justice and transitional justice. To implement the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law, to serve indigenous historical justice, and to lay the foundation for indigenous self- government - these are the three major goals for the government's policy towards indigenous peoples.

szy: mitakos kako ayza to itiniay, i tilibiay ato wangloay Incomin a salikaka, mapolong pawacay. mitakos kako titaan mikoking, caay ko pihosiw. miadasay tamowanan paicelang mitodawa, pasobana', palahci to nakamoan no Syifo, hay masalob ko tawyaay a ngangaw.
english: To all of our indigenous friends here and watching on TV and online: I invite you to stand witness. I invite you not to endorse, but to oversee. Please keep pressure on the government and right its course where necessary, so that it will realize its commitments and right historical wrongs.

szy: mikokay kako to polong no Incamin a salikaka, kamo ko pacekilay tina kanatal a tademaw, nipasazipa'an a lala', ato somamaday a laylay, inayi' ko pakademecay. o mahiniay, kona pabelien to kakasikazan, tongosay o aca.
english: I want to thank all of our indigenous friends. You remind everyone in this country that there is irreplaceable value in the land we tread on and the traditions we inherit. This value deserves dignity.

szy: zikoz to, pakayzaen niyam i picozoh to kawaw, teloc no binacadan, laylay no wawa wawa, ato Tawan a tadmaw amin no binacadan, caay to kalawpes ko kamo, caay to kapawan, mangaleb a caay to piliyas to lalangawan no ozip, caay to kapilakalak i no ozipan a lala'.
english: In the future, we will push for policies to ensure that succeeding generations of indigenous tribes and all ethnic peoples in Taiwan never lose their languages and memories, that they are never separated from their cultural traditions, and that never again are they lost in a land of their own.

szy: milongoc kako to polong no tademaw ita misaicelang, matineng to likisi ita, matineng to aenengan a lala' ita, a matineng to kasasizoma no binacadan a lalangawan. pasayza i masasonga'ay ay ko colil, pasayza i sikapolong asa maozip, pasayza i misabalohay ko nikaozip a Taywan.
english: I call upon our entire society to come together and get to know our history, get to know our land, and get to know the cultures of our many ethnic peoples. Let us work towards reconciliation, a shared existence and shared prosperity, and a new future for Taiwan.

szy: milongoc kako to binawlan no kanatal, ayza a demiad, misaicelang kita misakapah to kanatal ita, tatenga'ay o malacacayay ko kasasizoma no binacadan.
english: I call upon all citizens to seize the opportunities offered by this day - to join together, work hard, and build a country of justice, a country of true diversity and equality.

szy: kami o Sakizaya a tamdaw i ayaw no cacay a lasobo izaw ko tolo a bataan a mihcaan no madebekay kami a mapatay a tamdaw.
english: We Sakizaya was extinct one hundred and thirty years ago.

szy: nayay to ko ngangan i tini i hekal.
english: The name disappeared to the outside.

szy: saka tiza sa a mikapi i hiya i no pangcahan ko nikaozip aca no niyam.
english: So we lived under Amis with grievance.

szy: saka o zoma to haw koni o mikowanay toyni a kanatal saka.
english: So other people took over this island.

szy: palekalen no niza haw koni o binacadan.
amin haw no kasizomazoma toyni o yoancomin sananay i Taiwan.
english: All are the so-called indigenous people in Taiwan.

szy: saka kami saka molekal to kami.
kina pinaay haw a a saopo a masasosowal to pakainiay haw kami no sakizaya a kawaw.
english: We gathered many times and discussed things about Sakizaya.

szy: hepi mapacodad i tini i i yoanminhoei i tini sakakaay joseiin sananay.
english: registered as Council of Indigenous Peoples, Executive Yuan.

szy: saka na mahica saka kapah to.
kyo mapatizeng kami i Taiwan i mahini to sabaw tolo a minzok sananay a nikaozip.
english: So we were titled as the thirteenth indigenous people in Taiwan.

szy: saka motizeng to singangan to kita.
english: were set up and had our name.

szy: saka mi saka limolak amin ko balozo'.
kakilokilol sa to amin haw a manamoh.

english: We gathered and had a meeting.

szy: saka sayaway a mazateng niyam oyni to o palamal sananay a lisin haw noyni o hiya noyni o Sakizaya.
english: What we firstly thought of was the fire ceremony of Sakizaya.

szy: ano izaw henay ko palamalay i tini i Taiwan haw o noni o yoancomin sananay sa o Sakizaya.
english: If the indigenous people in Taiwan have fire ceremony, it is Sakizaya (that has it).

szy: o Sakizaya henay a tamdaw sa palamalay.
english: Sakizaya the people who light a fire.

szy: zay han oyni o lamal haw ko saka tebek a mapatay.

english: Sakizaya did not have its name.

szy: nika balcawaw ato ni o gongdong hananay a holam no nitodohan sa ko niyazo'.
english: Those who burned the tribe were the Mainland Chinese from Guangdong.

szy: kyo mabolaw talaco wa koni o sakizaya.
saka cacay a mihca ayza haw izaw to haw koni ka palamal no Sakizaya.
english: After one year (that we proclaimed our identity), there is a fire ceremony.

szy: saka o mapatayay i tawya henay saka kato od ko mapatayay a no Sakizaya a no oyni da da haw o talaayaway ko ozip o sEnEng saka makatolo a malebot.
english: There were many casualties of Sakizaya at that time, up to three thousand young people.

szy: makatokoh lima a malebot ko mapatayay.
english: And the number of dead people amounted to five thousand people

szy: tayda kita i omah miadih to nipalomaan a kobkob, pihaymawi to podoh ato wado!
english: We are going to see the corn we grow in the fields, but you need to be aware of the ants and bees.

szy: saydang a tayda kita i saowac midangoy haw?
english: Teacher, are we going to swim in the river?

szy: caay, a miadih/miazih kita to beded.
english: No, we are going to see dragonflies.

szy: saydang a tayda kita i omah paloma to lami' haw?
english: Teacher, are we going to grow some vegetables in the fields?
We are going to loosen the soil today.

szy: idaw i tida ko beded misabahebahel.
ayda henay kako makadih to maodipay a beded.
english: Today is the first time I see real living dragonflies.

szy: ye! hobaw! manamoh kako to adipapang, salongan.
english: Yeh! Wow! I love butterflies. They are very beautiful.

szy: i tida idaw ko sabahebahelay a adipapang.
caay kao adipapang koyda, o wado koyda.
english: Those are not butterflies. They are bees.

szy: kaitini to miazih, amana ka tayda/tayza i baatay a kakitidaan.
english: Come here and take a look. Don't go too far!

szy: hang, caay ka tayda/tayza kami i mabaatay.
english: Got it, we won't go anywhere too far.

szy: amana ka doba', pihaymawi mocolil mapolina.
english: Don't run and walk slowly lest you fall down.
I want to see them right away.
How do you go to the block-house?
How does he go to the hospital?

szy: colil han nida tayda i padekoan.

english: How do you go to Penghu?
I go to Penghu by plane.
I go to Penghu by boat.

szy: o canan ko kacawan iso taloma'?
o canan ko kacawan ni Panay tayda i cacodadan?
english: How does Panay go to school?

szy: makasilamalay ci Panay tayda i cacodadan.
english: Panay goes to school by train.

szy: o canan ko kacawan ni Tobah tayda i kiwkay?
english: How does Tubah go to church?

szy: makabatikal ci Tobah tayda i kiwkay.
english: Tubah goes to church by bicycle.

szy: makanolpin kiso tayda i cacodadan haw?
english: Do you go to school by MRT?

szy: caay, makabaso kako tayda i cacodadan.
english: No, I go to school by bus.

szy: makabatikal kiso tayda i cacodadan haw?
english: Do you go to school by bicycle?

szy: hang, makabatikal kako tayda i cacodadan.
english: Yes, I go to school by bicycle.

szy: makasiomalay kiso tayza i Takaw haw?
english: Do you go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail?

szy: hang, makasiomalay kako tayda i Takaw.
english: Yes, I go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail.

szy: tayda i Posong kiso makasilamalay o makahikoki?
english: Are you going to Taitung by train or by plane?

szy: makahikoki kako, makahikoki ko dadawaay to makasilamalay.
english: I will take the plane because it is faster than the train.

szy: tayda i kiwkay kiso makabaso o pacolil to kadideng?
english: Are you going to drive to the church or take the bus?

szy: pacolil to kazizeng kako tayza i kiwkay, pacolil to kazizeng ko calowayay to makabasoay.
english: I will drive to the church because it is more convenient than the bus.

szy: o cacakayan micapi' to loma' namo haw?
english: Is the market close to your house?

szy: caay kacapi', makaotobay kako tayda/tayza i cacakayan.
english: No, it is not, so I always ride the motorcycle to the market.

szy: macapi' ko payobinan to cacodadan haw?
english: Is the post office close to the school?
Yes, it is within walking distance.

szy: macapi' ko kakacawan to pikanan haw?
english: Is the restaurant close to the station?

szy: tahkal i pikacawan colil han lima a sasolitan katokoh to.
english: It only takes five minutes after you walk out of the station.

szy: maydih kako tayza mizizaw i tisowan.
english: I would like to visit you.

szy: sikawaw kako ayza caay kailoma' cilacila han to.
english: I am out today. How about another day?

szy: silawad kiso ancila haw? mamin malahok tayda kako mikilim i tisowan.
english: Then, are you available tomorrow? I'll visit you tomorrow afternoon.

szy: kapah to, halhalen ako kiso i loma'.
english: Sure, I will wait for you at home.

szy: hani taneng kako milingiha haw? maydih mikilo kako.
english: Would you mind if I do the voice recording? I would like to keep a record.
Would you mind if I do the video recording?

szy: la'cos azihen kako, caay kalisimet ko solo, haycan.
english: No, I am plain and the warehouse hasn't been tidied up yet.
Then I will just take photos.

szy: kokay koni pazizaw iso i takowan.
english: Thank you for accepting the interview.

szy: nayi' ko sapabaliw, o canan ko kaydihan no miso mipalita?
english: You are welcome. What would you like to know?

szy: hani o canan ko kawaw iso masakapah henay?
english: What do you do when you are young?

szy: o taylin kako iayaw, nika miales to kako ayza.
english: I was a police officer but I am retired now.
Then, are you working at the moment?

szy: hani i niyazo' moeneng ko wawa iso haw?
english: Do your kids live in the tribe too?

szy: caay, i tose moeneng ko wawa no mako.
english: No, my kids are all living in the city.
Then, do you live by yourself?

szy: pahabay henay kako to waco ato ayam, o loma' ay ako koheni.
english: I also keep a dog and a bird. They are my family.

szy: pahabay aca kako to cacay a nani', caay ka tibahaw izaw/idaw ko aadopan pacabayay.
english: I have a cat too. I won't get bored with the company of my pet.

szy: maydih a mipalita kako i tisowan to no miadopay a lisin.
english: I would like to ask you about the taboos of hunting.

szy: caay ka tineng ako, nika katinengan ako hamin han ako patobeli kiso.
english: I don't know much about that, but I will tell you everything I know.

szy: o sapiadop namo idaw/izaw ko lisin haw?
english: Do you have any taboos about hunting weapons?

szy: o sapiadop niyam la'cos ko tatayna mitiyong.
english: Our hunting weapons are untouchable to women.

szy: taneng ko tatayna miladay tayza/tayda miadop haw?
english: Then, can women go hunting together?
No, women cannot go hunting either.

szy: Komod, nayi' to ko epah i loma', katayda micakay to epah kiso.
english: Kumud, our home is out of rice wine, please go and buy some.

szy: idaw henay i palod ko cacay, sapica micakay!
english: There is still one bottle left in the kitchen, so there is no need to buy one!

szy: caay kataneng ko cacayay, picakay aca tosaen a langdaway taloma'.
english: One bottle is not enough for me, go and buy two more back.

szy: micakay to epah kako, idaw ko nipacakay namo haw?
english: I am looking for rice wine. Do you have any rice wine?

szy: idaw to! hacica ko nipicakay iso saw?
english: Yes! How many bottles do you need?

szy: tosa a langdaway ko nicakay ako, micakay aca to cacay tabo no belac.
english: I want two bottles and a pack of rice.

szy: iniw ko belac, maydih henay to canan kiso saw?
english: Here is the rice, what else do you need?

szy: a micakay henay kako to ti'kok, idaw/izaw haw ko no namo?
english: I want some eggs too, do you have some?

szy: mamin to mapacakay ko ti'kok niyam.

english: I want to buy some clothes.
What kind of clothes do you like?

szy: o apoyo'ay a ledong a zikoc/dikoc ko cakayen ako.
english: I want to buy the clothes with short sleeves.

szy: izaw ko domaay a kolit haw?
izaw henay ko salengacay ato somilaway niyam.
english: We have white and blue ones too.

szy: pabelien kako to cacay somilaway a zikoc.
english: Please give me the clothes in blue.

szy: Koli tacowa kiso nasawni? miwatawat kiso haw?
english: Kuli, where have you been just now? Did you go exercising?

szy: caay, tayza mipadang ci bai'an ako pacakay to lami'.
english: No, I went grocery shopping for my grandma.

szy: mahini sa, silawad kiso ansandeb? mapolonng kita malabi.
english: No wonder! Are you available at night? Would you like to have a meal with me?

szy: kai', tayda micakay to zikoc kako.
english: No, I want to buy some clothes.
Then, I will go with you.

szy: mahica to, hani pinaan kina lami' saw?
english: Hello, how much is this bunch of vegetables?

szy: cacay balod ko lami' tosa a bataan ko kalisiw.
english: The vegetables are $20 for a bunch.

szy: koyni a tobah pina ko kalisiw?
english: How much are these sweet potatoes?

szy: cacay a dadoy ko tobah tolo a bataan ko kalisiw.
pabelien kako to tosa balod a lami' ato cacay dadoy a tobah.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and a pound of sweet potatoes.

szy: Talib, katawalan ako ko sapisolit, taneng pacaliw kiso i takowanan haw?
english: Talib, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?

szy: nayi' ko no mako, ni Baloay koyni.
english: I don't have one either. This is Balu's.

szy: taneng pacaliwen henay kako haw? dadawa kako panokas i tisowan.
english: Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.

szy: kokay, padangen kako a mikokay ci Baloan.
english: Thank you and thank Balu for me.

szy: a panokas kako toyni tosaay codad.
english: I want to return these two books.

szy: hang i, idaw hen ko kaydihan?
english: No problem and what else do you need?

szy: maydih henay micaliw to toloay a codad kako.
english: I would like to borrow these three books.

szy: hanto. katineng tolo a demiad panokas han to.
english: Sure and remember to return them after three days.

szy: caay henay panokas kiso to sabolic i takowan.
english: You haven't returned me the eraser.

szy: kya caay to kaadih ko sabolic no mako.
english: Then, why is my eraser missing?

szy: sipacaliw to no miso ci nabaan.
english: Maybe you lend it to Maduhay.

szy: caay katineng kako. palitaen ako cinida.
english: I don't know. If so, let me go and ask her first.

szy: pacaliwen ako kiso no makoay a sabolic.
english: I will lend you my eraser first.

szy: Lengos, nipacaliw ni Ngayaw i tisowan kina kabong haw?
english: Lengus, did Ngayaw lend you this coat?

szy: caay, nicakayan ni ina ako pabeli i takowanan.
english: No, my mom bought it for me.

szy: malecad ko kabong iso ato ni Ngayaw.
english: Ngayaw's coat is the same as yours.

szy: o lomeni'ay ko kabong nida, caay kalecad ko kolit niyam.
english: His coat is black, so our colors are different.

szy: Panay, na micaliw kiso to kalisiw ci Kacawan haw?
english: Panay, did you borrow money from Kacaw?

szy: idaw, a panokas kako ayda a demiad cinidaan, katawalan ako ko kalisiw.
english: Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?

szy: ancila panokas han to no mako cinidaan.
english: I will return to him tomorrow.

szy: hang i, sakamo han to no mako ci Kacaw.
english: Okay, I will tell Kacaw for you.

szy: ka o ba'toay a sapibihkac to edo, ka o bihkac ko no tolok, mahini kya malocek.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay and catch bamboo partridges through qjiulang.

szy: mahiniay saca, mapatelac to kako, alaci' caay pakazakep kako.
english: No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

szy: a pasobana'en aca ako kiso hicaen misanga' ko tosaay lamangan a bihkac.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up these two traps.

szy: hang i, o matinengay to! mahini anoayaw a makala to aadopan kako.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

szy: tanaya' to ko lotok no omahay, kapiala to kakawit i solo kiso, taomah kita.

szy: i tapiingan no bilowa, comod han i solo maazih to iso.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.

szy: pihaymaw miala, amana kadoka masinang ko kakawit.
english: Be careful and don't get hurt. The sickle is very sharp.

szy: i sasa' oyza a kilang ko bihkac ako.

szy: pabacoen no mako i tini, matineng kako i cowaay ko bihkac ako.
english: I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.

szy: o pobo koyni, pazengen niyam i tapiingan no saowac sapiboting.

szy: nayi' ko pobo niyam i tiza, o sapacemod ko piboting niyam.

szy: caay henay pacemod kako, ano ayaw pasobana' han to iso kako?

szy: pasobana' han to ako kiso misanga' to pobo.
english: I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.

szy: mosaongay to ko sapacemod iso, hakya mokabit to ko boting, kabilil kiso tengtengen.

szy: a sawni to, mahoyahoy tato ko balonga. i tini kako motengteng to sapacemod, kaitida kiso miedap mowala to salil ako.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

szy: tengtengen iso patayni i takowan kya boting. padangen ako kiso motengteng.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

szy: kapahay to! yadah ko nikala ayza, matomes ko bilowa.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.

szy: kalamkamen ita taloma' paanin to katooday.
english: Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.

szy: amana to pibalakas, kabili mo'neng i poenengan.

szy: sakalima demiad no lipay ayza, mihibang anocila, maladay tahkal midang!
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!

szy: hang i! tayza i sa'wac kita.
english: Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

szy: sakatolo demiad no lipay anocila, anocila namalahok tayza mibalakas to mali kita!
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!
What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

szy: o pilipayan anocila, madih tayza i kiwkay kako ato ina.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.

szy: maydih maota' kako, maydih tayza i tatai'an.
english: I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

szy: saydan, adada' ko bili ako, maydih tayza i tatai'an.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.

szy: kapah tayza mibanaw to lima kako haw?
english: May I go wash my hands?
It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

szy: saydan, adada' ko tangah ako, namalahok amihibang.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

szy: saydan anoayaw sakacacay demiad no lipay amihibang kako, atayza papiazih to misaydan kako.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.

szy: adada' ko bili niza, i tatai'an ciniza.
english: She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

szy: saydan, adada' ko takolaw ni Ateng, mihibang ayza.
english: Teacher, Ateng has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

szy: ci Ba'to Kilang kako, cacay a bataan ko mihcaan ako ayza.
english: My name is Ba'tu Kilang, and I'm 10 years old.
What ethnic group are you from?

szy: loma'ay no miso hato o Yincomin haw?
english: Are all your family members indigenous?

szy: hang, hato o Sakizaya ko loma'ay niyam.
english: Yes, my whole family is Sakizaya.

szy: cayay, o Sakizaya ko wama ako, o Layak ko wina ako.
english: No, my father is Sakizaya, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

szy: ni Boting Tayto a wawa kako.
o wama iso koyza haw? pina to ko mihcaan niza?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

szy: cayay, o niyazo'ay a kalas niyam ciniza, walo a bataan to ko mihcaan niza.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

szy: pina to ko mihcaan ni kakama iso?
sabaw walo to ko mihcaan no kakama ako.
mihcaan ni kakama iso pina ko pikakaan tisowan saw?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

szy: lima a mihcaan ko laed niyam.
cacay a lasobo izaw ko sepat a bataan honan kako.
matenes to caay kasasoazih, talakaw to kiso?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

szy: hang, cacay a lasobo izaw ko tolo a bataan honan to kako.
hang, tolo a bataan dadoy to kako ayza.
atayza pisakakawaan mikilim to saydan kako.
english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.

szy: i pingadoyan ciniza, amadademec mingadoy asawni ciniza.
english: He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

szy: icowa ci Topos? amadademec madoba' asawni ciniza.
english: Where is Tupus? She's going to compete in a running competition later.

szy: i litang ciniza, awawen ako ciniza.
english: She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

szy: ayaw micakay to sakalahok kako, asawni to tayza mikilim tisowan.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

szy: pikilim to tao kiso, atayza mikilim to saydan kako.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

szy: ayza a demiad amadademec to coyciw ci Akih haw?
english: Is Akih competing in croquet today?
No, he's competing in high jump.

szy: pionnokayan a demiad amadademec kiso haw?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?
What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.

szy: pionnokayan apacakay to kakanan kita haw?
english: Will we sell food at the sports day?

szy: pakaala to icibang kiso, o mati:nengay!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!

szy: iniw to, i kakabian mabi' ciniza.
english: Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

szy: nayay, tahkal to nasawni ciniza, asandeb kya taloma'.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

szy: i sakatosa ciniza, katayza i pabaw kiso mikilim cinizaan.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

szy: ci Namoh, matenes caay to kaazih kiso, kapah to kiso haw?
english: It's Namuh. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?

szy: kapah to! tayni mikilim malpadang tisowan kako.
english: I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

szy: i palod miciyan to lami', awawen ako ciniza.
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.

szy: tayza i paloboan mizakep to tolakok ciniza.
english: She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

szy: caay ka i loma' ko baki namo, i omah ciniza, i loma' kamo mihalhal cinizaan taloma'.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.

szy: matenes caay kaazih, talakaw to kiso.
english: I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.
It's so good to see you.

szy: o sapabeli tamowan koyni a padingan, a pazengen i pingsyang.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

szy: matenes caay katayni, awawen ako ko katooday mapolong mokan.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

szy: sapica kalibotan to, ocya ko nanomen ako, tayni i tomonaw malpadang kita.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.

szy: kokay to pahalhal no miso, ataloma' to kako.
english: Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

szy: nasawni nipacokan koyni tolakok, pataloma'en haymaw han mokan.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

szy: nakamoan no miso ato ako anocila namalahok kapah to haw?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

szy: kapah to, nakamoan no mita icowa masasoazih?
nakamoan no mita cacodadan kapah to haw? amisasing kita.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

szy: tayza pakayingan kapah to, asilosid kako tayza.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

szy: niyazo'ay niyam a sakolal salongan ko bitelak. halhal to bitelak no balo katayni mikilim takowan!
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

szy: halhal katokoh to sadingsingan, maotang to!
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Then come during our Harvest Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

szy: hani kya malimad taloma' i niyazo' maozip kiso?
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.

szy: mahica caay ka i tokay pasobana' to codad?
english: Why not teach in the city?

szy: zayhan mabolah kako to niyazo' ako, maydih aca pasokas to niyazo'ay.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

szy: matineng mitenon kiso, cima ko pasobana'ay tisowan?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

szy: o bai ako, o samatinengay mitenon a tademaw no niyazo' niyam ciniza.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.
How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

szy: o lalangawan no niyam ko mitenon, maydih a panayat to lalangawan kako.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

szy: mati:neng kiso, matenes misaelaw toyni haw?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

szy: caay, pakala to cacay a lipay kapah to. ayawen mihodhod mingaay ko belac ato hakhak, palamel han to sapakolit papolong han mikiwakiw palalecad, pazeng han to i labo no tedos kapah to.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

szy: izaw itini ko no mako dokiyo ato daydam, hato nipalomaan no mako!
english: I have chili and lokiy, both grown by myself!

szy: hamin tosa konicakay pina ko kalisiw?
mapolong tosa a lasobo izaw ko lima a bataan ko kalisiw.
manamoh toyni a zikoc kako, pina ko kalisiw?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?

szy: lima a lasobo ko kalisiw noyni.

english: It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?
No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

szy: hang i, oyza lomeni'ay a zikoc ko kaydihan ako.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

szy: oyni sioy ato oyni bakan ko kaydihan ako.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

szy: polong tosa a malebot ko kalisiw, oyni nalimaan nisanga'an no mako, tatenga' matenes miyong.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

szy: siwkayen ako ko cabay tayni micakay, kapah ahemi'en toatodi' haw?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?

szy: hang! padangen kiso mipica' to walo.
english: Alright! I'll give you a 20% discount.

szy: awza azihazihen! izaw amin ko nipacakay to topel zikoc.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

szy: hani pina ko kalisiw no zikoc?
tolo a lasobo izaw ko lima a bataan ko kalisiw no cacay a zikoc. cacay a malebot ko kalisiw no toloay a zikoc.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

szy: cacay ko nicakay ako kapah to, pabelien kako to balohay.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

szy: mahica to, maydih kako micakay to hakhak ato makaw silaw.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and braised pork with maqaw pepper.

szy: mamin to mapacakay ko hemay. izaw henay ko tana' tinpola ako, maydih micakay kiso haw?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

szy: hang i! pabelien kako to cacay, anoayaw tayni to kako micakay.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

szy: hang, padangen ako kiso mipazeng i alobo, mahini lima a bataan ko kalisiw.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

szy: pitoay ko toki ako tayza i cacodadan ayza a demiad.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

szy: micodad to, micomod to ko saydan i cacodadan, sakamo sa ko mikeliday niyam," motizeng! mibaong!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

szy: tanotowa han niyam mosakamo," mahica to saydan."
yo picodadan sa, pasobana' ko saydan tamiyanan to aasipen a kamo no Sakizaya.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Sakizaya language of numbers.

szy: kilolen niyam ko saydan miasip, modadiw kami to aasipen a dadiw.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

szy: yadah to ko katinengan ako to kamo no Sakizaya.
english: I have learned many Sakizaya languages.

szy: dedemiad tayza kako i cacodadan, dedemiad minanam kako to kamo no Sakizaya, a mosakamo kako patengil ci inaan.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Sakizaya language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

szy: ci Asing ko ngangan ni ama ako.
ci Ipay ko ngangan ni ina ako.
cacay ko kakama ako, ci Kolas ko ngangan, sabaw cacay ko mihcaan niza ayza.
english: I have a brother, his name is kulas, he is 11 years old.
We study in the same school.
Both my brother and I like to sing.

szy: manamoh kako mingadoy, yo pihibangan sa, maladay amin kami o lalabo no loma' tayza mingadoy.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

szy: manamoh kako to balohayay a cabay, ngay a maladay kami modadiw ato mingadoy.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.

szy: lalima ko tademaw no loma' niyam.
english: There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

szy: mapolong kako aci ama, ina, kakama, kakana moeneng.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

szy: talakaw ci ama ako, o kingcal ci ama ako.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

szy: makodos ci ina ako, o misaydan ci ina ako.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

szy: i loma' hano o kamo no Sakizaya masasokamo ci ama i tamiyanan.
english: My father speaks the Sakizaya language with us at home.

szy: yo pihibangan no lalod taloma' namin kami i niyazo'.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

szy: maladay kako aci kakama, kakana tayza mizakep to balaot.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

szy: manamoh kako to lalabo no loma' a tademaw niyam.
english: I like our family very much.

szy: maladay kako aci ina midang ayza a demiad.
english: I went out with my mother today.

szy: langdaw ko tapoko no demiad, caay ka sienaw caay ka caledes ko demiad, banihiw ko bali.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

szy: i lotolotokan kami mokan to pang, mapacilal ko ozip, sadihko sa.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.

szy: kalahokan, masomad to ko tapoko somanah sa.
english: In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

szy: mipalita kako ci inaan, kya somanah ko tapoko.
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

szy: sakamo sa ci ina, hakay a tayni ko baliyos.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

szy: o labi nayay ko ladem i pabaw, tahekal to ko bonac.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

szy: taloma'ay a zazan, miyokiw kako to bonac.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

szy: adasay amana ka tayni ko baliyos, maydih henay kako tahkal midang.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

szy: i tepal no loma' niyam ko cacodadan, mocolil kako to dedemiad tacacodadan, mocolil aca taloma'.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

szy: caay ka tabaki ko cacodadan niyam, caay ka katood ko micodaday, masasotineng amin.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

szy: masaopo amin ipotah ko adiwawa, maladay mimali, pakongko.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

szy: maladay amin kami ato saydan misalama, mahiza o laboay no loma' ko cacodadan.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

szy: dedemiad miasik kami, a misadimel miasik to picodadan.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

szy: o zoma a tademaw misipo to sasingalan, o zoma sa miasik.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

szy: miasik aca kami to liwliw no cacodadan, mawawada' to kawaw, maaedap kami, tamelac sa to ko cacodadan to dedemiad.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

szy: nacila, tayza i niyazo' kako mizizaw ci bakian.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

szy: matenes to kami caay kasasokazih, mabolah kako cinizaan.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

szy: yo makaazih ci baki takowan pakan takowan to ciyak, ato ociya.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

szy: sicedam ko nipalomaan nibaki a ciyak, tatenga' aso'.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

szy: manamoh aca kako to ociya nibaki, aso' nanoman.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

szy: i kalahokan, maladay kako aci bai misakalahok.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

szy: sakaaso'an sa ko pisakalahok ni bai, izaw ko boting, tolakok, tamolak, ato katacomoli.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

szy: mamin malahok, tayza i bawbi kami milami'.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

szy: yadah ko nipiala ni bai to tobah, tali, ato dokiyo sapabeli takowan sakataloma' ako.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

szy: mikokay kako to henian, ano ayaw tayni aca kako mizizaw to henian.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

szy: ayza a demiad a ladayen kami no saydan tayza i paaadopan, masasilsil kami i panan micakay to paya.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

szy: comod sa kami i paaadopan, sakamo sa ko saydan, "no ayawan o ayamay, no zikozan o baoay, nanoozip han namo miazih."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

szy: matalaw kako to bao, kyo caay kako piazih to baoay.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

szy: yadah ko maazihay ako a ayam, bahebahel sa koheni i kilakilangan, maazih aca ko deko modeko i bohang no kilang a dibo.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

szy: i paaadopan izaw ko zo, sobayo ato tola', inaayaw caay henay kako pakaazih to aadopan, ayza a demiad manamoh kako makaazih.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

szy: yadah ko nisasingan ako, sapaazih ako ci amaan inaan.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

szy: anoayaw a maladay aci ama ina tayni.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

szy: pihibangan a lipay, tayza i Posong kako aci kakana mizizaw ci bakian.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

szy: namakay Taypak kami mikacaw to silamalay tayza i Posong.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

szy: katokoh to i Posong, makakazizeng ci baki tayni i pangizoan milikeloh tamian.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

szy: caay kabaat ko loma' nibaki to pangizoan, makakazizeng kasenong sa katokoh to.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

szy: i capi no loma' ni baki izaw ko tabakiay a papahotingan, maladay kami makabatikal tayza i papahotingan.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

szy: i papahotingan, ladayen ni baki kami pakan to sizi ato mikacaw to sobayo.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

szy: sansandeb, maladay kami tayza i nabakowan malabi'.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

szy: yadah ko kazizng i nabakowan, kyo makaotobay kami tayza.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

szy: yo a miliyas to kami sa, maazih makidem ko otobay, kacaw sato kami to baso miliyas.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

szy: ayza katokoh to kami i Taypak, mahicaay to hakya ko otobay ni baki matepaay to hakya.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

szy: yo adidi' henay i Takobowan ko loma' niyam, namicodad sato, malimad tayza i Taypak, hiza sato i tiza maozip.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Takubuwan. After I started school, we moved to Taipei and have been living in the city ever since.

szy: yo micodad sato i tabakiay a cacodadan, mitocek kako micodad to no Yoancomin lalangawan a codad, makatineng to Taywan Yoancominco izaw ko canacanan yadahayay a lalangawan.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

szy: sisa, ayza a mihcaan i pipahanhanan no lalod, taloma' i niyazo' kako aci kakama mizizaw to babalaki, maydih a makatineng to noozipay a binacadan a lalangawan.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

szy: waloay a bataan to ko mihcaan niza babalaki, nika azihen mahiza henay o masakapahay.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

szy: palitaan ako ciniza i cocowaan ko katinengan niza a kamo, matinengay ciniza mosakamo to kamo no Sakizaya, matineng mosakamo aca to kamo no Pangcah, Ngayngay ato Lipon.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Sakizaya, as well as Pangcah, Hakka and Japanese.

szy: palitaan ako ciniza kya matineng, alaw han yo adidi' henay ciniza minanam to to kamo no Sakizaya, acawa niza sa o Pangcah, i kakolian niza katood ko katinengan to Ngayngay a tademaw, kyo matineng ciniza mosakamo to cacanan a kamo.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Pangcah, and he knows many Hakkas at work, so he can speak so many languages.

szy: yo pizizawan niyam sa, yadah ko nisakamoan no babalaki to sakay piadopay a laylay a tineng.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

szy: kanahato caay katalesem kami a mitengil, nika hano limalay niyam a miloing, kya a satesek han to a mitengil.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

szy: yo adidi' henay kako caay ka tinetineng to no ozipay a binacadan a lalangawan, alaw han o Yoancomin ko ozip masikaz to.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

szy: yo yadah to ko katinengan sato sa, manamoh ka o Sakizaya a tademaw, o masazomaay, o kasasenengan aca.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Sakizaya is unique and something to be proud of.

szy: ayza a sansandeb, a taloma' to ci sabama.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

szy: tayza i iciba kako aci bayi micakay to tolakok sapatata' to aso'ay sakalabi ni sabama.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

szy: micaliway kami i pacakayay to lami', yadah ko mangadoay a lami'.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

szy: micakay kami to ingcay, koleto, ninzin.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

szy: i tepalay pacakayay to heci a tawki sakamo sa," sicedam ko padingad ato lopas ako, picakay to adidi' saw!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

szy: micakay kami to padingad ato lopas.
micaliway kami to pacakayay to titi, sakamo sa kya tawki, "o canan ko kaydihan namo saw? ayzaay a tolakok tabaki kizemo, cacay ko tolakok tolo a lasobo."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

szy: tada tekes sa ci bayi, mipalita to tawki kapah ahemi'en to adidi' haw sa.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

szy: nika sakamo sa kiza tawki ahemi'ay to ko aca, laecos to a miselep.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

szy: i tepalay a tawki sakamo sa katayni micakay to boting ako, tabaki aca ahemi' aca ko boting ako.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

szy: sazikozay micakay kami to tolakok micakay aca to boting, taloma' sa cacay a takal ko nisalami'.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.

szy: matenes to a mohalhal, doot to ko demiad.
english: After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

szy: pakatelay ci sabama sakamo sa, caay aca pahanhan sa ko hitay, ano ayaw to a lipay kya taloma'.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

szy: sakamo sato ci bayi yadah to ko nisalami'an, awawen ko katooday tayni mokan!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

szy: awawen niyam ko laloma'an ato cabay, mapolong mokan to yadahay a sakalabi.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

szy: izaw ko cacay a kapot ako ci Paliho, hina makatawal ciniza to cacanan.
english: I have a classmate named Palihu, he often forgets to bring things.

szy: yo a micodad to sa, micaliw to ciniza to sapisolit, sasipo, ato sasolitan.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

szy: kinacacay, kinatosa, kinatolo, pacaliwen henay no katooday ciniza to cacanan.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

szy: nika laecos ko mahiniay a wayway niza, hina caliw to cacanan caay pacobelis.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

szy: sazikozay caay to pacaliwen no katooday to cacanan i cinizaan.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

szy: o cacay a demiad, maladay amin kami tahekal midang.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

szy: teban no zazan, akenih ci Paliho a motayi', makatawal moala to sapisingat ciniza.
english: On the way, Palihu wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

szy: a micaliw ciniza i kapot to sapisingat, nika patobelien amin no kapot inayay ko niala ako sa.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

szy: akenih to ci Paliho moangic to. mabaloco' ciniza sakamosa, kya caay amin kamo pacaliw to sapisingat i takowan!
english: Palihu burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

szy: sakamo han to no kapot, zayhan caay pikelid kiso to cacanan nomiso, saaca nipacaliwan niyam tisoan a cacanan, caay aca kiso pacobelis!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

szy: tocila micodad, matabal ci Paliho katokoh to i cacodadan, pacobelisen amin ni Paliho ko nicaliwan to cacanan i kapot.
english: The next day at school, Palihu arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

szy: papisolol ci Paliho to kapot, sakamo sa anoayaw ako to ko mokeliday to cacanan, kokay to kapot noayawan pacaliw kamo i takowan to cacanan.
english: Palihu apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

szy: o miadopay no niyazo' ci ama ako.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

szy: yo adidi' henay kako, tahekal ci ama aci sinaama i labi, mokelid to sapiadop a bakan ato kowang.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

szy: takelal to sa, miawit to nikaala a niadopan taloma' koheni.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

szy: alahican o kiwmah, alahicaan o lawal, alahican makaala to tolakok.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

szy: i sacomodan no niyazo' silsilen to noheni ko nikaala a niadopan, sapawada' to binawlan.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

szy: sawsawni milimola' kako ci amaan, maydih a mikilol ci amaan miadop.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

szy: sakamo sa ci ama anobalaki to kako a ladayen ako kiso miadop.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

szy: o niyazo'ay a tatama matineng koheni o bihekac ko sapiadop, misanga' aca koheni to bantek ato o baeto ko sapenec to bihkac.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

szy: matinengay ci ama ako misanga' to bantek, sakamo sa ci ama, sapibihkac to tolakok koyni, sameteken miazih ko nazipaan no aadopen, pazengen ko bihkac i nicolilan no aadopen.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

szy: maydih kako kalamkam a balaki maladay to babalaki miadop, dedemiad minanam kako misanga' to bihekac, kalamkam sato nisanga'an ako a bihekac makaala to to aadopan.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

szy: namakaazih ci ama sakamo sa anoayaw o matinengay a miadopay kiso sa.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

szy: balaki to kako ayza, konoyen ako ko sapiadop a pana' ato betil, mikilol ci amaan miadop.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

szy: taloma' to i niyazo' sa ya nikaala a niadopan pawada'en to niyazo'ay a binawlan.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

szy: sakamo sa ci ama, a mikokay kita to Dieto to pipakalemed ititaan, kyo yadah ko nikaala nomita to niadopan.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

szy: maotang to kako tacodadan to sananal.
english: I was late for school this morning.

szy: tayza i cacodada hawsa, makatawal ako mikelid ko kabong.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.

szy: nayi' ko nikelid ako to canan a toodan.
english: I didn't bring anything with me.

szy: micodad hawsa, mapolong miazih to codad kako ato kapot.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

szy: miseking hawsa, pacaliwen no kapot kako to sapisolit ato sabolic.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

szy: sakamo sa ko saydan takowan, "anoayaw katabal molkal to sananal, amana to kaotang!"
english: The teacher told me, Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

szy: ci Ateng ko kapahay a cabay ako, o Sakizaya aca a awawa ciniza.
english: My good friend's name is Ateng, and he is also an Sakizaya child.

szy: maladay kami micodad i Sakol a niyazo'.
english: We study together in the Sakul tribe.

szy: hina maladay kamin mitengil to kongko no kalas, matineng amin kami mosakamo to kamo no Sakizaya.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Sakizaya proficiently.

szy: talakaw kizemo aca kako, mapolet makodos aca ci Ateng.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Ateng is short and thin.

szy: sisatahaw ci Ateng, manamoh amin ko katooday cinizaan.
english: Ateng is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

szy: ayza a demiad piondokayan no cacodadan, mikawaw ko cacodadan to yadahay a nikasedsedan.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

szy: izaw ko matatengtengay, mitokod to mali, madoba', mapalaw ato miacin.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

szy: yo madobak kako hawsa, mapolin kako, yadah ko izang no tosoz.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

szy: nika motizeng kako, malalid taayaw madoba'.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

szy: katokoh kakatangasaan lipahak amin ko tademaw.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

szy: kanahato caay pakala to icibang, nika manamoh kako, zayhan malepon to ako ko kadademec.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

szy: nacila ako ato wama tayza mizizaw to sinawama ako.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

szy: madoka to ko koko' ni sinawama.
sakamoen niza kami, mapeci' mabohang ko badahong no loma'.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

szy: misakapah to badahong ciniza sa, makay badahong madebay to.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

szy: mikelid ciama to titi no katalalan ato da'dac pabeli ci sinawamaan.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

szy: i kakabi'an masasokamo kako ato sinawama, yadah ko nipaselay niza to kongko.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

szy: ayaw amiliyas kako, miseneng ci sinawama takomaw talakaw to sa, mangaleb masomad malakapah to.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

szy: sakako, "halhalen kapah to ko koko' ni sinawama, anoayaw katayni i loma' niyam midang."
english: I said, When your foot gets better

szy: i 2022 a mihca, cenbo palecapo matatengil pasisil i minbonsiw to ngangan no Yincomin.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

szy: matenes to ko pipalita ako to cenbo milongoc to minbonsiw "pasisil to ngangan no binacadan" no niyazo'ay masakapahay Kilang Boting.
english: I interviewed Kilang Buting, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

szy: matatelekay to ciniza ato ako koyni pilipayan tayza i loma' niza mipalita cinizaan.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

szy: i pipalitaan, misiwkay ciniza takowan to kakayzaan a ngangan niza, mikelid takowan matineng to loma'ay niza, niyazo'niza.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

szy: mipalitaen kako cinizaan kya pacici' amisomad to nganga, malomanay nipangangan a kawaw la'tos haw?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

szy: mosakamo takowan ciniza, zayhan o layak ko codad caay ka locek pakatokoh to ngangan niza, zoma moawaw henay cinizaan "Kilang seynsey," sakasa o kakatawaan.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Kilang Xian Sheng

szy: sakamo sa ci Kilang Boting, kamo no, "Yincomin nisolitan a ngangan kya tatenga'ay a ngangan no niyam. ngangan no mako tongosay to binacadan niyam, ngasaw niyam, singangan niyam, maydih taneng katood ko binacadan mikilim pataloma' to ngangan no ozipay."
english: Kilang Buting said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

szy: nacila tayza pipacakayan misiwbay kako acibai, yadah ko nikelidan ni bai to nipalomaan niza tayza, misanga' aca to aso'ay a kakanan no Yincomin pabeli to katooday.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

szy: manamoh ko katooday to pipacakayan nibai, katood ko micakayay to kakolot naso ato daydam, katood ko tayniay a tademaw mitanam to nisalami'an niza.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the bitter gourd and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

szy: aso' kaen ko nisalami'an niza to pahko ato hakhak, izaw henay nisalami'an to kiwmah a titi makaw silaw, malilid no sanek ko katooday a labang, tayni amin ko katooday misilsil to pipacakayan niyam.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

szy: misalami' cibabi hawsa, i tapiingan kako mikawih to labang. tonotowa' sa kako i tapiingan, "no ozip amin nipalomaan a lami', cayay ko nipasapayoan, kabili tayni micakay yo!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

szy: kalamkamen amamin to mapacakay ko tood niyam, sakamo sa cibai, "zayhan hato nipipadang iso."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

szy: oyni a kawaw, mananam to kako makayniay Yincomin no molangaway ato kakanen a natinengan, saca mataneng to ngelo' no pipacakayan.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

szy: maazih to ko kanamoh nibai to sakay babalaki a kakanan, tada malemed ato paseneng.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
